<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0090</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0090</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written Evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">IAA</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA (Independent Academies Association) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the national membership organisation for leaders of academies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are a non-partisan representative organisation committed to supporting our members in the advancement of the education and life chances of all pupils and students in our care. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An acknowledged and respected national body, we are ‘the voice of academies’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, run by and on behalf of our continually growing membership. We play a leading role in the development of the wider academy movement, providing help, support and advice to existing, new and converting academies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are the only independent organisation d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">edicated to supporting academies and have a track record of over 20 years’ experience in providing leadership to all types of state-funded independent schools.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our work includes lobbying </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">government and opposition on matters relating to education policy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it affects academies.</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA (Independent Academies Association</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) firmly believes that the overarching principle and foremost priority of the academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">movement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is the urgent need to deliver high quality education to all students and pupils.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Evidential data demonstrates that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme has been effective in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">raising standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, with the impact being greatest among sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More could be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">done to incentivise increased numbers of good and outstanding converter academies to sponsor failing schools, particularly those that predominantly serve disadvantaged children.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accelerated pace of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has caused some issues, most notably in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the variable quality of sponsors and governing bodies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When problems occur in this area, they must be resolved more quickly than hitherto. Further reform of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">governance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is recommended.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Any temptation to reinvent the ‘middle tier’ along </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">previous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> authority lines should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resisted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: instead, greater impetus should be provided to system leadership </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on a sub-regional basis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as part of a truly self-improving system.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> continue to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have strategic and statutory roles to play but they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">must not be at the expense of academy independence or autonomy.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA welcomes the introduction of sub-regional Schools Commissioners and Headteacher Boards as a proportionate response to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the ongoing expansion of the academies programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy chains have a crucial role to play in the new educational landscape, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many demonstrating outstanding ability to transform education</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.4pt; text-indent:-21.55pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy status is equally relevant to primary schools as it is to secondary schools and growth in the number</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s of primary academies should be supported and encouraged.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The effectiveness of academisation in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2010, the NAO noted that, o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">verall, academies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increase</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the rate of improvement in GCSE results when compared wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">th their predecessor schools. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the proportion of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academy students</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> achieving five or more A*-C </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at GCSE</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> improved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at a faster rate than in maintained schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, particularly those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with similar intakes</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2011 and 2012 schools with academy st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">atus made, on average, more progress between KS2 and GCSE than schools without academy status</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Those sponsored academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that were established early on in the programme replaced the worst schools in the country and, in nearly every case, transformed provision and dramatically and very rapidly improved outcomes. The focus was on removing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from the system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the rump of the 200 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">owest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> performing schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, where underperformance was historically endemic and stubbornly ingrained and which were situated in some of the most disadvantaged and challenged areas of the UK. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The fact that the early academy sponsors turned around these schoo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ls in the most </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">difficult</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of circumstances, with few very failures, is testament to the efficacy of the programme and it is, therefore, no surprise that we have recently witnessed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resurgence in this approach</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which is welcomed by our association.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It can also be no accident that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">success of initiatives such as London Challenge was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> contemporaneous with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a period of mass academisation of schools within the area.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The most compelling evidence for the effectiveness of academies has come in the recently</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> published Ofsted Annual Report, which notes that: </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 14.2pt 10pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sponsor-led academies are delivering a step change in performance for chronically</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> underperforming schools. Academies established in 2007 have narrowed the attainment gap of five or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">more A* to C grades at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">GCSE, including English and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mathematics, by eight percentage points.</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The report also goes on to state that “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy converters are outperforming all non-academy schools” and that “Sponsor-led academies that have been open since 2007 have made the most im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provement at Key Stage 4”, suggesting that the longer an academy is established, the greater its impact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> over time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">￼</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA acknowledges</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and welcomes the moves made by Ministers in recent times to increase the rigour in selecting academy sponsors / free school proposers, in assessing the capacity of existing sponsors to take on additional academies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and in pausing or halting the expansion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of chains where there have been concerns about academic performance or financial management.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">leading to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ministerial approval and subsequent academisation remains unwieldy and can be painfully slow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not only for the prospective sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but for the children attending </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">failing schools, their parents </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">staff working in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Schools can find themselves in a protracted state of limbo, where uncertainty and the inability to move forward can impact detrimentally on stakeholder confidenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, the quality of provision and sometimes on outcomes.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he DfE might usefully consider further refinements to the two approaches to academisation, the so-called ‘fast-track’ and ‘fully sponsored’ routes, which are rightly based on assessments of potential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">risk, in order to ensure that, where necessary, children’s education can be transformed without delay. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">With regard to the programme as a whole, however, in some ways the converse is true, as t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accelerated pace of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has caused some issues, mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">st notably in the variable quality of sponsors and governing bodies.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When problems occur in this area, they must be resolved more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">readily</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than hitherto. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Department should act more quickly to reassign a sponsor/trust where a mistake has been made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Existing governing bodies of schools rated less than good by Ofsted should not be involved in choos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing their own academy sponsor. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is appropriate that, where a local authority has worked closely with a school and knows it well, they should have a voice i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n respect of the choice of sponsor but the local authority should not have any power of veto.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We acknowledge that there is less “soft sponsorship” of schools than was the case at one time, but more can still be done and similar ‘tightening up’ may be nee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ded in the free schools programme. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To support sponsor selection and to ensure rigorous accountability, we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> need a transparent, easy to access register of sponsors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for each sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> includes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a list of schools they run</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> judgments of each of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hose schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s in progress and attainment that have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been achieved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Further reform of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">school </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">governance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to align it more with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the most successful practice in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the business sector, is recommended</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very clear and transpar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent accountability, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">much smaller boards of non-executive directors, fewer committees and more performance management of governors than is currently the case in the majority of schools and academies.  Within a group setting, the role of the Executive Princi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pal / Chief Executive Officer with regard to governance should be more clearly defined and emphasised, as should that of other Executive Directors.  I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t may be that radical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transformation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of governance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is required in order to help bring about the next step </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">change in the education system as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Certainly there remain issues with the recruitment and retention of governors, directors and trustees of sufficient calibre and with adequate capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to fulfil the roles and duties as currently defined and govern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment would do well to consider means of incentivising the best people to take up these positions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and to encourage businesses to promote them amongst their workforce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">upport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the benchmarking of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Headteachers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of failing schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, recognising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that in some cases, for instance where the Headteacher is a recent appointment, a change in leadership may not necessarily be the most appropriate course of action</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Our association would defend </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">compulsion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a route to academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it should always </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">based on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sound </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sophisticated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> judgement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a school’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> performance and capacity to improve (or otherwise).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important that academisation is not seen as a punishment but is viewed as being of benefit to children, young people and a lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cal community. The DfE may wish to review what messages are communicated to schools ‘in scope’.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Hitherto, conversion to academy status has involved the closing of the predecessor school/s and reopening as a new school: this process should be maintained as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there needs to be every opportunity to rebrand, ‘re-culture’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and adopt new approaches.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Free S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chool</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> programme should be more systematically targeted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in areas of basic need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (i.e. where there is a significant shortage of school places).</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also believe t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is appropriate to open free schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">quality of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provision is poor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and standards are low.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ny</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mechanism for opening </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">new </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">schools must be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">balanced</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by a mechanism for closing schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that suffer from endemic poor performance.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  The option of closure should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be a mandatory consideration every time a school faces compulsory conversion </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to academy status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">under threat of being moved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to another sponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4.18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At the opposite end of the spectrum, an outstanding school that is a member </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of an academy chain should have the option to leave its group and set up as a separate sponsor and take on one or more failing schools, providing that doing so will demonstrably not impact negatively on the capacity of the existing sponsor.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">the Secretary of State in intervening in and supporting failing academies, and how this role will work as the programme expands</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The number of academies whose performance causes concern is a very small percentage of the total.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The current mechanism of issui</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng sponsors with pre warning notices and, if subsequently necessary, warning letters, has led to considerable and quick improvements in these academies.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In extreme circumstances, where it is considered that standards are unlikely to rise quickly enough, it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is right and proper that the Secretary of State direct a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ponsor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important, however, that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">action </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ecisive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and taken without undue delay, in order that children do not miss the opportunity of a good quality education.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As the programme expands further, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the systematic growth of school-to-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">school support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will be essential, especially as the Secretary of State implements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a model of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">devolution to regional regulatory and advisory bodies, as described below, founded on the work</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of successful system leaders and the Office of the Schools Commissioner.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It will be a vital corollary to such a framework that the identification and development of these system leaders is accurate and valid.  Therefore, schools and academies should onl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y be judged ‘outstanding’ by Ofsted if they can demonstrate that they are outward-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">facing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that they have successfully led school improvement beyond their individual institution.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hope that the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the ‘P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rogress 8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will lead to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a better understanding of what is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an outstanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in terms of making a difference to children’s learning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">what makes an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> outstanding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> leader</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The functions and responsibilities in relation to academies and free schools </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of local authorities and other organisations operating between the Secretary of State and individual schools; what these functions and responsibilities should be; and what gaps there are in support for schools at this level</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Local authorities should: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strategic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vision for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economic and social </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">development of their defined local area; set key goals; identify challenges</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and provide the framework within which all education and training providers can eff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ectively operate in partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Clarit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y is needed regarding the duties of local authorities with regard to education, which should be limited to a narrow set of statutory functions, e.g. safeguarding children, admissions and special educational needs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t is important that all statutory servic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es that local authorities provide are of high quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, any local authority powers, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">relate to promoting high standards in schools, should not impinge on academy independence or autonomy: to do so would undermine a fundamenta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l premise of the academies movement, namely that with greater freedoms come greater responsibilities. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Within this context, it is inappropriate for local authorities or, indeed, the Department for Education (DfE) to have a role in ‘supporting’ academies an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d free schools. It is far more fitting and sustainable in the long term to seek to promote a self-improving system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where the very best practitioners are always </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">outward looking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and help others to improve rapidly through a school-to-school model.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lcomes recent statements from Ministers and officials regarding the intention to regionalise more of the DfE’s work and to devolve certain functions and powers to sub-regional Schools Commissioners and Headteacher Boards.  It is wholly appropriate to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more use of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">successful </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">system leaders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in this way and to exploit the local knowledge of those closer to the chalk face than officials in Whitehall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by devolving as many powers as possible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If, as has been suggested, these new bodies are to be responsible </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the early identification of underperformance and for brokering improvement and/or structural solutions, then they should also carry overarching duties in respect of overall performance within their sub-regions. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In conjunction with the sub-regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Headteacher Boards, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t may be appropriate to consider a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n expanded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">role</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for NLGs (National Leaders of Governance), perhaps in an advisory capacity and/or by establishing regional panels of NLGs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as a resource to assist with the devolved system leadership fun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ctions.  For instance, outstanding Chairs of Governors might be able to advise on sponsor selection. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What role academy chains play or should play in the new school landscape; how accountable they are; and what issues they raise with regard to governance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">arrangements</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy chains have a crucial role to play in the new educational landscape, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with many demonstrating outstanding a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bility to transform education. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he most successful epitomis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> outstanding governance, leadership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and financial management and have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rapidly and dramatically improved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> provision and outcomes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in schools where previously there was endemic failure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The very best chains focus on a particular local area, where they maximise the benefits of joint staffing, CPD and economies of scale wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hin a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">shared vision and ethos. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">They expand in a measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> manner, building capacity just ahead of need and ensure an unrelenting focus on the core purposes of teaching, learning and achievement.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As an association, we support and encourage the regionalisation of l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">arge national chains in order to achieve the benefits outlined above.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The IAA is in favour of strong </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">accountability and s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">upport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the inspection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by Ofsted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Chains should be subject to a desktop data dashboard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> exercise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> highlighting the performance of schools within the group. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Where the desktop </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">analysis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">shows a chain’s performance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> less than good, they will be subject to inspection.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This exercise should NOT be based on an aggregate average of the academies’ perfor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mance within the chain but where there is any individual academy facing performance problems, they should be identified and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the sponsor </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">questioned.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no ‘one size fits all’ approach to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the establishment, structure or modus operandi of multi-academy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trusts or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chains, meaning that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be flexible and inspections differentiated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">varying contexts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also see a place for a searchable directory of academy sponsors / free school operators (see </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> above) which, as with the inspect</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion of chains, should include intelligent, sophisticated and contextualised judgments that take into account improvement trajectories, for example the time taken by a sponsor to move a predecessor school in special measures to a good or outstanding academy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">financial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘top slice’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">levied by a chain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should be more transparent and included in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this directory (or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chain performance tables</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, comparing like for like and detailing the services that are provided for this fee. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, it is appropriate for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EFA to audit c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hains</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to ensure sound financial management and governance and value for money use of public funds.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In respect of governance arrangements, c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hains </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">must be free </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to decide what is appropriate for them and the communities they serve. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> should be transparency about structure, resources and decisions, and a clear expectation that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">community voice will be heard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The appropriateness of academy status for primary schools and what special factors apply;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">and what evidence there is that aca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">demy status can bring value for money either for individual primary schools or for the system as a whole</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy status is equally relevant to primary schools as it is to secondary schools and growth in the numbers of primary academies should be supported </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and encouraged.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Academy status represents a particular mind-set and approach to leadership and management, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complete responsibility for the performance of one’s own organisation is adopted and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">academisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is appropriate for any school, irr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">espective of age phase or size.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, there are certain challenges that can be faced by small schools in respect of the additional responsibilitie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s that come with academy status, difficulties in creating a high reliability organisation (given the increa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sed likelihood of key person dependency) and the sustainability of leadership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Therefore, cluster arrangements are sometimes appropriate and are often most effective when one or more outstanding school is part of the group.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whether such arrangements are o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the basis of a primary only collaborative, ‘a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ll through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’ structures or otherwise cross-phase, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">greater v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">alue for money </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can be achieved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economies of scale</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the group can recruit and retain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">high</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> quality staff </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">committed to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the cluster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, new career pathways can be developed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the opportunities to share staff, best practice and CPD across and between schools within the group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are beneficial to the raising of standards.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.29pt; padding-left:3.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">failing primary schools</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Closure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ard federation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with an outstanding academy or cluster as described above.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a hre